Let's say I have:
```csharp
bool Test1(uint a)
{
    return a >= 1;
}

bool Test2(uint a)
{
    return a == 1 || a > 0;
}

bool Test3(uint a)
{
    return a > 0;
}

```

I expect them all to generate the same asm (see [godbolt](https://godbolt.org/z/IiY8Q_)), at least the 1st and the 3rd cases, but instead I get:
```asm
; Method PP:Test1(int):bool:this
G_M35066_IG02:
       cmp      edx, 1
       setae    al
       movzx    rax, al
; Total bytes of code: 10


; Method PP:Test2(int):bool:this
G_M35065_IG02:
       cmp      edx, 1
       je       SHORT G_M35065_IG04
       test     edx, edx
       setne    al
       movzx    rax, al
G_M35065_IG03:
       ret      
G_M35065_IG04:
       mov      eax, 1
; Total bytes of code: 20


; Method PP:Test3(int):bool:this
G_M35064_IG02:
       test     edx, edx
       setne    al
       movzx    rax, al
; Total bytes of code: 9
```

if we normalize `X>=C` to `X>C-1` we can get for free bound check eliminations for cases like this (see https://github.com/dotnet/coreclr/issues/21408):
```csharp
void WriteTrue1(char[] a)
{
    if ((uint)a.Length >= 4) // bounds checks are removed only if we use '> 5' here
    {
        a[0] = 'T';
        a[1] = 'r';
        a[2] = 'u';
        a[3] = 'e';
    }
}
```

Something similar is already done for signed comparisons, see https://github.com/dotnet/coreclr/blob/master/src/jit/morph.cpp#L12778-L12783 
(but only for C=1).
so
```csharp
bool Test1(int a)
{
    return a >= 1;
}

bool Test3(int a)
{
    return a > 0;
}
```
both generate the same asm with `test edx, edx`.

